

html

unlike a scripting or programming language that uses scripts to perform functions, a markup language uses tags to identify content. 
<p>
paragraph
</p>

the html document has opening and closing html tags.
these tags, like the bread in a sandwich, surround everything else:

<html>
…..
<html/>


the head of an html file contains all of the non-visual elements that help make the page work.

<html>
<head>.....</head>
</html>

the body tag follows the head tag.

html files are text files, so you can use any text editor 

to place a title on the tab describing the web page, add a <title> element to your head section:

in html, there is a list of elements that specify text style.

<html>
   <head>
      <title>first page</title>
   </head>
   <body>
      <p>this is regular text </p>
      <p><b> bold text </b></p>
      <p><big> big text </big></p>
      <p><i> italic text </i></p>
      <p><small> small text </small></p>
      <p><strong> strong text </strong></p>
      <p><sub> subscripted text </sub></p>
      <p><sup> superscripted text </sup></p>
      <p><ins> inserted text </ins></p>
      <p><del> deleted text </del></p>
   </body>
</html> 

html includes six levels of headings, which are ranked according to importance.
these are <h1>, <h2>, <h3>, <h4>, <h5>, and <h6>.

it is not recommended that you use headings just to make the text big or bold, because search engines use headings to
index the web page structure and content.


to create a horizontal line, use the <hr /> tag. 

the browser does not display comments, but they help document the html and add descriptions, reminders, and other notes.
<!-- your comment goes here --> (no ! mark in the end)

html documents are made up of html elements.

an html element is written using a start tag and an end tag, and with the content in between.
html documents consist of nested html elements
some html elements (like the <br /> tag) do not have end tags.
it’s a separate, single element.

attributes provide additional information about an element or a tag, while also modifying them. 
attributes are always specified in the start tag, and they appear in name="value" pairs.
<p align="center"> 
   this text is aligned to center
</p>


attribute measurements 
<hr width="50px" />

the align attribute 
  <hr width="10%" align="right" /> this is also a text.

the <img> tag
inserts image and does not contain closing tag 
for url use src attribute 
syntax
<img src="image.jpg" /

Links

To add a link inside the webpaege it requres <a> tag and the href attribute to define the lnk's
 destination address:  <ahref="url"></a>

_blank is used to specify where to open the linked document:
<ahref "url"target="_blank"> smth </a>

Lists
Ordered list => to use <ol> tag and <li> to define the list item 
<html>
<head>
<title>smth</title>
</head>
<body>
<ol>
<li>C_1</li>
<li>C_2</li>
<li>etc</li>
</ol>
</body>
</html>
Unordered lists => to use <ul> tag which will mark by bullets instead of numbers.

Table
<table> tag creates a table which are divided into tabel rows using <tr> tag,
the rows are divided into the columns with the <td> tag.
<table>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</table>

<table border ="5">
<tr> 
<td>1</td>
<td>2</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><br/></td>
<td colspan="4"><br/></td>
</tr>
</table>

rowspan attribute makes more than one row 

<table align="center">
<td bgcolor="red">text</td> [an attribute to change the colors]

Headers 

<th> is the headers 
